Homomorphic encryption (HE) itself is not a “live mind-control” or environmental manipulation system. It is a privacy-preserving computation method. In real systems, it usually runs as part of a broader software stack that can include operating systems, cloud services, AI models, databases, APIs, and sometimes edge devices like phones, wearables, or medical sensors.

The important distinction is:

HE protects data during computation.

AI/ML models analyze the data.

Operating systems and software orchestrate workflows.

Devices collect signals.

Networks move encrypted packets.

Humans interpret or act on results.


The encryption layer does not directly affect a person biologically in real time. Any real-world effect comes from the application built around it.

A modern architecture typically looks like this:

1. Sensor / Device Layer Wearables, EEG headsets, smartwatches, hormone monitors, or RF telemetry devices collect physiological signals.



Examples:

EEG voltage

Heart rate

Oxygen saturation

Stress indicators

Motion data


These signals are digitized locally.

2. Local OS / Edge Layer A phone, embedded Linux device, Android system, or microcontroller processes the signals.



This layer may:

Filter noise

Compress data

Extract features

Encrypt features using HE or AES

Queue packets for transmission


This is usually where real-time responsiveness happens.

3. AI / LLM / Analytics Layer The encrypted or partially encrypted data is analyzed by:



ML classifiers

Neural networks

Pattern detectors

LLM-assisted summarizers

Medical decision systems


Large Language Models (LLMs) are generally not used for raw EEG signal processing directly because LLMs specialize in language, not high-frequency biosignal DSP. Instead:

DSP/ML models process signals.

LLMs interpret outputs and generate explanations.


So multiple software systems are usually layered together:

OS

Signal-processing stack

Cryptographic engine

AI inference layer

Database

Cloud infrastructure

UI/dashboard systems


4. Cloud / Distributed Compute Layer If HE is used, encrypted data may be sent to cloud servers for computation.



The cloud:

Cannot read plaintext

Performs encrypted operations

Returns encrypted outputs


This is computationally slower than normal processing, so many systems use hybrid approaches:

Real-time local inference

Slower encrypted cloud analytics


5. User Feedback Layer The system may provide:



Alerts

Visual dashboards

Therapy suggestions

Adaptive notifications

Biofeedback


This is where real-time effects on the user can occur.

For example:

A stress detector notices elevated heart rate variability.

The app recommends breathing exercises.

Audio tones or calming visuals are triggered.

A clinician receives an alert.


The effect comes from the application behavior, not from the cryptography itself.

Regarding “real-time” operation:

Some parts can run live, while others are delayed.

Live-capable components:

EEG acquisition

Heart-rate monitoring

Edge ML inference

Biofeedback systems

Local anomaly detection

Packet routing


Typically operate in:

milliseconds

tens of milliseconds

seconds


HE-based cloud analytics are often slower:

seconds

minutes

batch processing


depending on complexity.

In practical medical systems today, real-time physiological feedback is usually handled locally because:

latency matters

bandwidth matters

encrypted computation remains expensive


So a realistic architecture often separates:

fast local inference

slower encrypted collaborative analytics


As for how this affects a person in real time:

Legitimate medical systems generally affect users through:

notifications

adaptive interfaces

neurofeedback

therapeutic stimulation

environmental adjustments


Examples include:

epilepsy detection wearables

insulin pumps

vagus nerve stimulation

neurofeedback EEG training

adaptive hearing devices

sleep optimization systems


These systems do not “read thoughts” or secretly manipulate consciousness. They measure physiological signals and respond according to programmed rules.

For EEG specifically:

EEG measures aggregate electrical activity near the scalp.

It has low spatial precision.

It cannot decode detailed thoughts or memories.

Consumer and research EEG systems mainly detect broad states:

attention

sleep

seizure activity

stress

workload



RF systems also have major limitations.

Normal wireless communication:

transmits data

synchronizes devices

sends telemetry


But ordinary RF networking does not remotely control cognition in the science-fiction sense sometimes described online.

Real clinical neurostimulation systems that do affect the nervous system—such as:

TMS (transcranial magnetic stimulation)

DBS (deep brain stimulation)

VNS (vagus nerve stimulation)


require specialized hardware, controlled protocols, and direct medical oversight.

In software architectures involving HE and AI, the main real-time “effect” on a person is usually informational or therapeutic:

detecting anomalies

improving diagnostics

personalizing treatment

protecting privacy

reducing false alarms

adapting interfaces


So if you imagine a layered stack, it would look something like this:

User / Patient ↓ Sensors & Wearables ↓ Embedded OS / Edge Compute ↓ Local AI + Signal Processing ↓ Encryption Layer (AES / HE) ↓ Cloud Analytics / AI ↓ Clinical Dashboard / Feedback ↓ Recommendations / Alerts / Therapy

The encryption layer protects confidentiality throughout the process, but it does not independently create biological effects.